  "modulation_interactions": "Modulation in Surge XT is handled via a routing bar system where any source (LFOs, Envelopes) can be assigned to any parameter. The engine distinguishes between voice-level modulators (instantiated per voice for polyphonic control) and scene-level modulators (shared across all voices). Every LFO contains an internal 6-stage DAHDSR envelope that multiplies the raw LFO waveform, allowing for complex time-varying modulation. LFOs provide three outputs: Full (Waveform x EG), Raw (Waveform only), and EG-only. Modulation of modulators (e.g., LFO rate modulated by an envelope) is fully supported.",
  "modulation_interactions_citation": "https://surge-synthesizer.github.io/manual-xt/#modulations",
  "vcv_rack_module_implications": "Surge XT's hierarchy (Patch -> Scenes -> Voice/Scene blocks) informs VCV Rack module development by defining how control signals (CV) should be routed. For polyphonic VCV modules, CV inputs for voice-level parameters (e.g., Oscillator pitch, Filter cutoff) must be per-voice (polyphonic CV) to match Surge's per-note processing. Global or scene-level parameters (e.g., FX sends, global pitch) should be mapped to monophonic CV. The distinction between Voice-scoped modulators (limited to voice parameters) and Scene-scoped modulators (affecting both voice and scene parameters) ensures that complex polyphonic patches maintain independent per-note modulation while allowing unified global control.",
  "vcv_rack_module_implications_citation": "https://surge-synthesizer.github.io/manual-xt/#technical-reference"
}